imensions of rationality and advances the Enlightenment project, buffering it against the postmodern critique that the movement fails to appreciate aesthetic experience.Guided by the work of Jürgen Habermas, Donald Davidson, and a range of media theorists, including Marshall McLuhan, Vogel rebuilds, if he does not remake, the relationship among various forms of media—books, movies, newspapers, the Internet, and television—while offering an original and exciting contribution to media theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMass mediaxPhilosophy. 0aRationalism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh1 aArnold, Darrell.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/voge1505840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231527750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231527750/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK